<TITLE> Putin to kick off Duma election campaign in weeks </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MOSCOW, Aug 14 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Russia's President Vladimir Putin will kick off the country's electoral season near the start of September, the head of the Central Election Commission said on Tuesday. Election campaigns for the country's lower house of parliament, known as the Duma, will get underway once Putin formally signs the appropriate decree, Vladimir Churov said. The vote is due to take place on Dec. 2. The Duma polls, which are widely expected to consolidate the control of pro-Kremlin parties over the legislature, are widely seen as a rehearsal for presidential elections next March. Putin has promised not to seek a third term, but has made clear he wanted one of his allies to become the next president. The Kremlin is seeking to ensure a smooth transition of power. Churov was quoted by Interfax as saying Putin would sign the decree "On September 1, plus or minus two to three days." Churov predicted that voting in the country of 142 million would pass off without incident on the "calmest safest, sunny frosty day", according to Ria news agen
